  "suggestion": "[narrative-psychology+personality+social-cognition+identity-theory] IMPLEMENT NOW — Narrative Agency × Communion Spine (McAdams 1993). The model has `person.history?: string[]` but never uses it. Extract two dimensions from history: agency (self-directed action themes: 'I decided', 'I achieved', 'I refused') and communion (relational themes: 'we connected', 'I helped', 'I belonged'). Function: `extractNarrativeTheme(history) → { agency: number, communion: number }` — scan history strings for agency/communion keywords, normalize to [0,1]. Then modulate attractor depths: attractors aligned with the person's narrative schema get depth ×1.5 (reinforced identity), misaligned attractors get depth ×0.5 (identity threat). High-agency persons respond to threats with assertion/control; high-communion persons appease/seek connection. This is ~30 lines reusing the existing attractor system and explains why identical situations produce opposite responses in different people — a major coverage gap. — Math: narrative_vec = [agency, communion]; attractor_alignment = cos(attractor_vec, narrative_vec); depth' = depth × (0.5 + alignment); [dynamical-systems+topology+catastrophe-theory+polyvagal-theory+clinical-psychology] Hysteretic Catastrophe Gate (René Thom + Porges). The current polyvagal gate uses sigmoid — smooth and reversible. Real autonomic regulation is hysteretic: entering SHUTDOWN requires less arousal than exiting it (once flooded, hard to regulate). Replace the sigmoid autonomic scoring with a cusp catastrophe potential V(x) = x⁴/4 − a·x²/2 − b·x where a = chronic stress load (history depth) and b = acute arousal. The stable minima of V are the autonomic states. Hysteresis emerges naturally: the fold in the cusp means SHUTDOWN has a different entry threshold than exit threshold. Add a `persistenceState` variable that carries autonomic state across the computation — once SHUTDOWN, it takes a 0.3 arousal drop to return to MOBILIZED. Explains trauma (permanent basin shift), why willpower fails under stress, why panic attacks are self-sustaining. — Math: V(x, a, b) = x⁴/4 − a·x²/2 − b·x; stable states at dV/dx = 0; hysteresis width = 2·sqrt(a/3); entry_threshold ≠ exit_threshold; [pragmatic-linguistics+philosophy-of-language+social-cognition+computational-linguistics] Gricean Pragmatic Inference Layer. The model reads stimulus.description literally. Humans read it pragmatically: Grice's cooperative maxims (quantity, quality, relation, manner) — when violated, the violation itself carries signal. Add a `inferPragmaticContent(stimulus) → { impliedValence: number, impliedThreat: number, subtext: string }` layer before the main prediction pipeline. Detect: quantity violation ('they said nothing' → social threat inferred), quality violation (hedging language 'fine', 'whatever' → suppressed negative), manner violation (vague/indirect → concealed conflict), relation violation (non-sequitur response → deflection). Each violation type maps to a prior over hidden emotional states. Inject these as synthetic beliefs into the active inference pass. Covers the entire domain of indirect communication, passive aggression, stonewalling, and social anxiety — all currently invisible to the model because it only processes explicit content. — Math: P(hidden_emotion | utterance) ∝ P(utterance | cooperative) × P(maxim_violation_type); implicature_strength = 1 − P(cooperative | utterance)",
